---
import HelloWorld from '../components/HelloWorld.jsx'
import Counter from '../components/Counter.jsx'
import Greeter from '../components/Greeter.jsx'
import CounterWithHeader from '../components/CounterWithHeader.jsx'
import UserCardDemo from '../components/UserCardDemo.jsx'
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Getting Started with Sygnal</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles/guide.css" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <header class="hero">
        <h1>Getting Started with Sygnal</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
          An interactive guide to building applications with Sygnal.
          Each example below shows the code alongside a <strong>live, working component</strong> you can interact with.
        </p>
      </header>

      <nav class="toc">
        <h2>Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#hello-world">Your First Component</a></li>
          <li><a href="#counter">Interactive Counter</a></li>
          <li><a href="#mvi">Model-View-Intent</a></li>
          <li><a href="#greeter">Working with User Input</a></li>
          <li><a href="#child-components">Adding Child Components</a></li>
          <li><a href="#state-passing">Passing State to Children</a></li>
          <li><a href="#next-steps">Next Steps</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <!-- ─── Section 1: Hello World ─── -->

      <section id="hello-world">
        <h2>Your First Component</h2>
        <p>
          The simplest Sygnal component is a function that returns JSX, with an
          <code>.initialState</code> property providing the starting state.
        </p>

        <div class="example">
          <div class="example-code">
            <h3>Code</h3>
            <pre><code>function HelloWorld(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;Hello &#123;state.name&#125;!&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

HelloWorld.initialState = &#123;
  name: 'World'
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="example-demo">
            <h3>Live Demo</h3>
            <div class="demo-frame">
              <HelloWorld client:load />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>
          This component reads <code>state.name</code> and renders it. The state is
          set once via <code>.initialState</code> and provided to the function
          automatically. No hooks, no setup &mdash; just a function and a property.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 2: Counter ─── -->

      <section id="counter">
        <h2>Interactive Counter</h2>
        <p>
          Static content isn't very exciting. To make things interactive, we add
          two more properties: <code>.intent</code> and <code>.model</code>.
        </p>

        <div class="example">
          <div class="example-code">
            <h3>Code</h3>
            <pre><code>function Counter(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;Count: &#123;state.count&#125;&lt;/h1&gt;
      &lt;button className="increment"&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
      &lt;button className="decrement"&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

Counter.initialState = &#123; count: 0 &#125;

// Intent: WHEN should things happen?
Counter.intent = (&#123; DOM &#125;) =&gt; (&#123;
  INCREMENT: DOM.select('.increment').events('click'),
  DECREMENT: DOM.select('.decrement').events('click')
&#125;)

// Model: WHAT should happen?
Counter.model = &#123;
  INCREMENT: (state) =&gt; (&#123; count: state.count + 1 &#125;),
  DECREMENT: (state) =&gt; (&#123; count: state.count - 1 &#125;)
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="example-demo">
            <h3>Live Demo</h3>
            <div class="demo-frame">
              <Counter client:load />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 3: MVI Explanation ─── -->

      <section id="mvi">
        <h2>Model-View-Intent (MVI)</h2>
        <p>
          Sygnal uses a pattern called <strong>Model-View-Intent</strong>. The
          counter above demonstrates all three pieces:
        </p>
        <ol class="mvi-list">
          <li>
            <strong>View</strong> (the function) &mdash; <em>How</em> things look.
            Renders the UI based on the current state.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Intent</strong> (<code>.intent</code>) &mdash; <em>When</em>
            things happen. Listens for DOM events and maps them to named actions.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Model</strong> (<code>.model</code>) &mdash; <em>What</em>
            happens. Defines how each action updates the state.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>Data flows in one direction:</p>
        <div class="flow-diagram">
          DOM Events &rarr; Intent &rarr; Model &rarr; State &rarr; View &rarr; DOM
        </div>
        <p>
          Notice that event handlers are <strong>never</strong> attached in the
          JSX. Instead, <code>.intent</code> uses the DOM driver's
          <code>.select()</code> and <code>.events()</code> methods to observe DOM
          events declaratively. The DOM selector is isolated to the current
          component, so simple class names work perfectly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 4: Greeter ─── -->

      <section id="greeter">
        <h2>Working with User Input</h2>
        <p>
          Two-way data binding is easy. The <code>.map()</code> method on a stream
          lets you extract data from DOM events before passing it to the model.
          Try typing in the input below:
        </p>

        <div class="example">
          <div class="example-code">
            <h3>Code</h3>
            <pre><code>function Greeter(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;Hello &#123;state.name&#125;!&lt;/h1&gt;
      &lt;input className="name-input" value=&#123;state.name&#125; /&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

Greeter.initialState = &#123; name: 'World' &#125;

Greeter.intent = (&#123; DOM &#125;) =&gt; (&#123;
  CHANGE_NAME: DOM.select('.name-input')
    .events('input')
    .map(e =&gt; e.target.value)
&#125;)

Greeter.model = &#123;
  CHANGE_NAME: (state, data) =&gt; (&#123; name: data &#125;)
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="example-demo">
            <h3>Live Demo</h3>
            <div class="demo-frame">
              <Greeter client:load />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>
          The <code>.map(e =&gt; e.target.value)</code> in the intent extracts the
          input's value from the DOM event. The <code>data</code> parameter in the
          model reducer receives whatever the intent stream emits.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 5: Child Components ─── -->

      <section id="child-components">
        <h2>Adding Child Components</h2>
        <p>
          Components nest naturally, just like in React. Import a child and use it
          in the parent's view. Props are passed as attributes:
        </p>

        <div class="example">
          <div class="example-code">
            <h3>Code</h3>
            <pre><code>// Header.jsx
function Header(&#123; title &#125;) &#123;
  return &lt;h1&gt;&#123;title&#125;&lt;/h1&gt;
&#125;

// CounterWithHeader.jsx
import Header from './Header.jsx'

function CounterWithHeader(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;Header title="My App" /&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;Count: &#123;state.count&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
      &lt;button className="increment"&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

CounterWithHeader.initialState = &#123; count: 0 &#125;

CounterWithHeader.intent = (&#123; DOM &#125;) =&gt; (&#123;
  INCREMENT: DOM.select('.increment').events('click')
&#125;)

CounterWithHeader.model = &#123;
  INCREMENT: (state) =&gt; (&#123; count: state.count + 1 &#125;)
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="example-demo">
            <h3>Live Demo</h3>
            <div class="demo-frame">
              <CounterWithHeader client:load />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 6: State Passing ─── -->

      <section id="state-passing">
        <h2>Passing State to Children</h2>
        <p>
          By default, child components receive the entire application state. To
          give a child only a slice, use the <code>state</code> prop with the name
          of the property to pass:
        </p>

        <div class="example">
          <div class="example-code">
            <h3>Code</h3>
            <pre><code>// UserCard.jsx
function UserCard(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div className="user-card"&gt;
      &lt;h2&gt;&#123;state.name&#125;&lt;/h2&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;Age: &#123;state.age&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
      &lt;button className="birthday"&gt;
        Have Birthday
      &lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

UserCard.intent = (&#123; DOM &#125;) =&gt; (&#123;
  BIRTHDAY: DOM.select('.birthday').events('click')
&#125;)

UserCard.model = &#123;
  BIRTHDAY: (state) =&gt;
    (&#123; ...state, age: state.age + 1 &#125;)
&#125;

// UserCardDemo.jsx
import UserCard from './UserCard.jsx'

function UserCardDemo(&#123; state &#125;) &#123;
  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;Full app state: &#123;JSON.stringify(state)&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
      &lt;UserCard state="user" /&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
&#125;

UserCardDemo.initialState = &#123;
  user: &#123; name: 'Alice', age: 30 &#125;,
  settings: &#123; theme: 'dark' &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="example-demo">
            <h3>Live Demo</h3>
            <div class="demo-frame">
              <UserCardDemo client:load />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>
          <code>UserCard</code> only sees <code>&#123; name: 'Alice', age: 30 &#125;</code>
          as its state &mdash; not the entire app state. When it updates its state
          (via the birthday button), the change flows back up to
          <code>state.user</code> in the parent automatically. Watch the full state
          JSON update above the card when you click.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── Section 7: Next Steps ─── -->

      <section id="next-steps">
        <h2>Next Steps</h2>
        <p>You've seen the core patterns. Here's where to go from here:</p>
        <ul class="next-steps-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Collections</strong> &mdash; Render dynamic lists with filtering
            and sorting using <code>&lt;collection&gt;</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Switchable Views</strong> &mdash; Swap between components based
            on state for routing-like behavior with <code>&lt;switchable&gt;</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Custom Drivers</strong> &mdash; Wrap APIs, localStorage, or any
            async operation as a driver with <code>driverFromAsync()</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Context</strong> &mdash; Pass values to all descendants
            regardless of depth.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>TypeScript</strong> &mdash; Full type definitions included for
            type-safe components.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Read the full
          <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal/blob/main/docs/guide.md">Guide</a>
          and
          <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal/blob/main/docs/api-reference.md">API Reference</a>
          for details on every feature.
        </p>

        <h3>Example Projects</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal-todomvc">Sygnal ToDoMVC</a>
            (<a href="https://tpresley.github.io/sygnal-todomvc/">Live Demo</a>)
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal-2048">Sygnal 2048</a>
            (<a href="https://tpresley.github.io/sygnal-2048/">Live Demo</a>)
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal-calculator">Sygnal Calculator</a>
            (<a href="https://tpresley.github.io/sygnal-calculator/">Live Demo</a>)
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <footer>
        <p>
          Built with <a href="https://github.com/tpresley/sygnal">Sygnal</a> +
          <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a>
        </p>
      </footer>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
